\par <I> <h> }{<#/>}{\f0\fs24\lang2057  }{\b\f0\fs24\lang2057 Another winning chance for Gor}{\f0\fs24\lang2057  </h>
\par }{<#/>}{\f0\fs24\lang2057 Gor Mahia, Kenya's representatives in the continental club championships - the quarter-finals of the Africa Cup of Clubs - go on parade tomorrow against Sudan's
 El-Hilal in Khartoum. <#/>Their fans, as indeed every Kenyan, are expected to be rooting for them.
\par <#/>After their impressive performance two weeks ago, when they whipped the Sudanese 2-0 in Nairobi, they should not find it too difficult to dismiss their hosts.
\par <#/>However, the fact that Gor are in Sudan and ready for battle should not overshadow the tribulations they went through to raise money for the trip. <#/>And once again, the role of the Ministry of Culture and Social Services, the Kenya National Sp
orts Council and the Department of Sports in the promotion of sport is questionable.
\par <#/>These are the Government organs charged with sport but they have such serious handicaps that they end up frustrating rather than promoting sport. <#/>It is a credit to
 Gor and the many well-wishers who boosted their kitty that they have made it to Sudan.
\par <#/>About five years ago, Gor won the Africa Cup-Winner's Cup (the Mandela Cup). <#/>They were the first club from the East and Central Africa region to attain that lev
el of success. <#/>It was sweet victory and the entire nation associated with it. <#/>But Kenyans, particularly sports officials, need to associate themselves with the team's development and not merely wait to sing its praises on the victory podium.

\par <#/>That aside, our concern now is that Gor will not be overwhelmed by the intrigue and other problems attendant upon their preparation for the match.
\par <X_>}{\v\f0\fs24\lang2057 At the moment, Kenya's soccer performance is not at its best and needs dramatic achievements to inject more
 life into it. Of course, we remember the Africa Cup of Nations debacle in Senegal early this year, the ignominious exit of AFC Leopards from the Africa Winner's Cup and Kisumu Posta's humiliation in the newly-introduced CAF Cup. The one thing which could
 recoup some of our lost pride is Gor's victory in the Africa Cup of Champion Clubs.
\par }\pard\plain \s45\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\lang2057 {\v\f0 Back home, we are wishing Gor the very best of luck - and they need plenty of it - to advance not only to the semi-finals but to the finals and victory in the prestigious c
hampionship which may give us something to enthusiastically bellow about again.
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20\lang1031 {\v\f0\fs24\lang2057 Good luck, Gor. }{\f0\fs24\lang2057 </X>
