\par <I> <h> }{<#/>}{\f0\fs24\lang2057  }{\b\f0\fs24\lang2057 Airport personnel we do not need}{\f0\fs24\lang2057  </h>
\par }{<#/>}{\f0\fs24\lang2057 Tourism has over the last few years overtaken coffee as the country'
s main foreign exchange earner. <#/>More and more tourists have been visiting this country mainly because of its attractions compared to the rest of the continent.
\par <#/>The majority of these tourists enter the country through the airports in Nairobi and Mom
basa. <#/>The government has put a lot of effort in improving means of communication in the country. <#/>Airfields and airports rank high among these developments. <#/>Despite these efforts, there have been many complaints not only by tourists but also by
 local people concerning the conditions of major airports. <X_>}{\v\f0\fs24\lang2057 The complaints range from corruption to broken facilities.
\par The first impression one gets at a foreign airport is long lasting. if this impression is negative, the visitor is unlikely to visit ag
ain. Worse still is the negative publicity he will spread when he returns to his country. This is bad for a country that has so much at stake in tourism.
\par The Press has often carried letters by tourists listing the treatment they get at the airports as the 
worst experience of their otherwise exciting visit to this country. They shower praise on the friendly people in the countryside, the unpolluted beaches and the unspoilt game parks. All this however is spoilt by what they experience at the airports. Quite
 often, they land on potholed runways, then they go through rigorous and at times unnecessary customs and immigration searches. As if that is not enough, the basic facilities such as toilets are either broken, missing, or untidy.
\par But what is most annoying to the tax payer is the fact that a lot of money is spent by the government to build and improve these facilities, yet the people supposed to take care of them simply do not do so.
\par Why, one wonders, do we have to have <-/uncourteous> and incompetent people 
at our points of entry? Why is it that the best qualified, the best in public relations, the best disciplined people are not deployed at our airports? Corruption, inefficiency and crime will only drive away our visitors to other destinations.
\par The latest fr
om a Minister in the Office of the President, Mr Burudi Nabwera, is that the government is about to start a Shs 1.6 billion rehabilitation exercise at the Jomo Kenyatta and Moi International airports. All this is welcome news for these airports really nee
d
 some facelift. But we feel that before such a heavy financial commitment is undertaken, a lot more needs to be done in terms of training and retraining of  the personnel who are the first and the last to see our visitors. It should be appreciated that we
 can have the most beautiful airports in the world but which bring very little income because tourists avoid them.
\par Let us build new airports and expand and rehabilitate the old ones. We should, however, also seriously think of the personnel who will man those facilities. Corrupt, incompetent and uncouth personnel do not belong there. }{\f0\fs24\lang2057 </X>
