\par <I> <h> }{<#/>}{\f0\fs24\lang2057  }{\b\f0\fs24\lang2057 KPDA's strike can only worsen things}{\f0\fs24\lang2057  </h>
\par }{<#/>}{\f0\fs24\lang2057 
During these difficult times, the last thing Kenyans would like to see is an action that is likely to add an extra burden on their shoulders. <#/>Already, most of the people have been stretched to the limit as a result of the ever-increasi
ng prices of commodities.
\par <#/>To the ordinary Kenyan, the strike threat by the Kenya Petroleum Dealers Association issued on Thursday, is another attempt to inflict even more suffering on them. <#/>This is because the extra profits the dealers are asking f
or are likely to be passed on to the consumers in the form of a price increase.
\par <#/>If the dealers had been arguing that they do not make any profits from selling petroleum products, the reaction from the public may have been more sympathetic. <#/>However,
 in this case, we have been told by the Government and the dealers themselves that the issue is the size of the profits.
\par <#/>According to a statement issued last night by the <-/Permament> Secretary for Energy, Mr Chrispus Mutitu, the petrol dealers make a profit of Sh650 on every 1,000 litres of petrol sold. <X_>}{\v\f0\fs24\lang2057 
And even if one takes into account the overheads, there is reason to believe that dealing in petroleum products is not a waste of time.
\par Judging from what happened in Nairobi yesterday morning, we w
ould like to advise the petroleum dealers that their boycott threat is a negative move that they should seriously reconsider. The panic-buying witnessed in the city is an indication of the kind of chaos that the dealers' selfish move can unleash.
\par We are not in any way suggesting that the dealers are not justified in feathering their own nests. But if they do this at the expense of wreaking havoc on the strategic sectors of the economy that need this fuel, then they are being unpatriotic.
\par The timing of the d
ealers threat, too, appears disturbing. It is obvious that the General Election is just round the corner. By trying to hold the Government to ransom through this kind of threat, the dealers we are inclined to suspect - have a hidden agenda, most likely po
litical.
\par That is why we feel the dealers should withdraw their boycott threat immediately and use other means of solving this problem. But if they go ahead and press ahead with this move, which we are informed is aimed at ensuring that they get an extra Sh5
59 million in profits a year, we suggest that the Government takes steps to ensure that our economy is not thrown into disarray just to fill the stomachs of a few Kenyans.
