\par }{<#/>}{\f0\fs24\lang2057 Though the recent mass resignations from }{\i\f0\fs24\lang2057 The}{\f0\fs24\lang2057  }{\i\f0\fs24\lang2057 Nation's}{\f0\fs24\lang2057  newsroom seem 
to have a cause external to and apart from tribalism at the Nation Centre, the fact is that the Nation Group is top-heavy with one tribe. <#/>Though it is by no means true that the present management is what is responsible for the tribal lopsidedness, the
 fact remains that there is that disease in that publishing company which requires urgent treatment.
\par <#/>}{\i\f0\fs24\lang2057 The Nation's}{\f0\fs24\lang2057  editor, though Kikuyu, fully merits his recent appointment into that berth. <#/>He is among the ablest pressmen in this country today. <#/>
Yet his reply the other day to accusations by politicians that }{\i\f0\fs24\lang2057 The Nation}{\f0\fs24\lang2057  has a "tribal agenda" left many loopholes through which malevolent and unscrupulous individuals can continue to hit }{\i\f0\fs24\lang2057 
The Nation}{\f0\fs24\lang2057  below the belt.
\par <#/>The political charge that }{\i\f0\fs24\lang2057 The Nation}{\f0\fs24\lang2057 
 is there only to serve Kikuyu interests could very well be a "lie", as the editor asserted. <#/>But the fact remains that the degree of domination of that organization by one tribe is unjustifiable and unacceptable for a newspaper which is always ready w
ith similarly pontifical commentaries against other organizations.
\par <#/>So, although the editors was justified in trying to clear his present management's name from the tribal sins of past managements, those who watched at close quarters as this domination 
was building up also expect the editor to publish a programme through which the publishing company is hoping to redress these injustices by certain managements in the past.
\par <#/>Without that the editor was still laying his company open to attack. <#/>And a rival daily newspaper, }{\i\f0\fs24\lang2057 The}{\f0\fs24\lang2057  }{\i\f0\fs24\lang2057 Kenya Times}{\f0\fs24\lang2057 
 - which the editor had accused of complicity in the "lie" against }{\i\f0\fs24\lang2057 The Nation}{\f0\fs24\lang2057  - took full advantage of just that fact to publish a list purporting to show that }{\i\f0\fs24\lang2057 The Nation's}{
\f0\fs24\lang2057  newsroom is a tribal parish. <#/>}{\i\f0\fs24\lang2057 The Kenya Times}{\f0\fs24\lang2057  could have gone further to show the degree of domination in other departments.
\par <#/>It is not our intention to pat }{\i\f0\fs24\lang2057 The Kenya Times}{\f0\fs24\lang2057  on the back. <#/>A public war of words between two of the main news publications cannot augur well for journal
ism in this country. <#/>And, as our reporter shows on Page 4, the holier-than-thou attitude taken by }{\i\f0\fs24\lang2057 The Kenya Times}{\f0\fs24\lang2057  may itself invite public scrutiny. <X_>}{\v\f0\fs24\lang2057 
As far as tribalism is concerned, almost all publishing companies - like almost all other walks of life in Kenya - have tribal skeletons in the cupboard.
